00:01:14.830 --> 00:01:16.580
So bring everybody
you know for that.

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:18.060
It's free.

00:01:18.060 --> 00:01:21.275
And once again, there will be a
concert reflection, as we know.

00:01:21.275 --> 00:01:24.330
So turn it over to
Neil, welcome him.

00:01:24.330 --> 00:01:24.830
Thank you.

00:01:24.830 --> 00:01:27.700
NEIL LEONARD: Hi.

00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:34.134
So I'm going to give a
short presentation on a work

00:01:34.134 --> 00:01:35.800
I've created, a little
bit of background

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:39.450
and why I made the
work, and leave you

00:01:39.450 --> 00:01:42.630
with an assignment,
which is to create

00:01:42.630 --> 00:01:46.750
your own work along the
same lines and with the idea

00:01:46.750 --> 00:01:49.640
that when I come
back next Monday

00:01:49.640 --> 00:01:52.460
I'll be able to hear what
you guys have come up with.

00:01:52.460 --> 00:01:54.110
And we could even play together.

00:01:54.110 --> 00:01:58.270
So this is all kind of going
in the direction of you taking

00:01:58.270 --> 00:02:02.290
some of these ideas and
running with them on your own.

00:02:02.290 --> 00:02:07.000
I have a background
as a jazz saxophonist

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:13.090
with some activity in the area
of fine arts, which kind of

00:02:13.090 --> 00:02:17.820
means that I've always had not
like a singular vision of what

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:19.430
I want to do, but
I've always kind of

00:02:19.430 --> 00:02:22.310
been looking on the
peripheral for other things

00:02:22.310 --> 00:02:24.450
that will be interesting.

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:29.920
When I was a teenager,
really, I played in bands

00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:30.880
in Philadelphia.

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:34.140
And one of the bands
that I was part of

00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:37.214
had these two brothers
Robin and Kevin Eubanks.

00:02:37.214 --> 00:02:38.880
And Kevin Eubanks,
you might have known,

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:40.710
was the band director
of the Jay Leno Show

00:02:40.710 --> 00:02:42.820
for I think about
18 years or so.

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:44.730
And he recently retired.

00:02:44.730 --> 00:02:50.030
And his older brother, Robin,
is going to, as Mark said,

00:02:50.030 --> 00:02:52.470
participate in the
concert on Wednesday

00:02:52.470 --> 00:02:54.470
evening, fantastic
trombone player.

00:02:54.470 --> 00:02:58.480
So he's a guy I've
known as a kind

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:02.670
of young musician
in Philadelphia.

00:03:02.670 --> 00:03:05.210
And that was sort
of the background

00:03:05.210 --> 00:03:07.127
I came from, just kind
of people playing jazz,

00:03:07.127 --> 00:03:09.210
a little bit of pop musical,
a little bit of funk,

00:03:09.210 --> 00:03:11.640
occasionally a Latin gig, as
a teenager in Philadelphia

00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:13.616
before I moved out
of Philadelphia

00:03:13.616 --> 00:03:14.615
to go to a conservatory.

00:03:19.250 --> 00:03:23.750
In the course of
playing the saxophone,

00:03:23.750 --> 00:03:28.780
I came across a few things
which really interest me.

00:03:28.780 --> 00:03:31.110
One was a reel-to-reel
tape deck.

00:03:31.110 --> 00:03:34.870
So the school I went to had
a small electronic music

00:03:34.870 --> 00:03:41.900
studio with a EMS synthesizer
and a two reel-to-reel tape

00:03:41.900 --> 00:03:42.700
decks.

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:47.090
And we were essentially
just shown this stuff

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:50.100
and invited to come
to use it somehow.

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:53.500
And at that time, I was really
interested in pop music.

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:55.130
That was kind of
before jazz, I had

00:03:55.130 --> 00:04:01.020
listened to pop music that
had very interesting things

00:04:01.020 --> 00:04:02.250
happening in the production.

00:04:02.250 --> 00:04:04.740
So this would be Jimi
Hendrix, Pink Floyd,

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:07.550
you name it bands of say
the '70s, so to speak,

00:04:07.550 --> 00:04:10.180
if I can really date myself.

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:13.450
And I began to teach
myself a little bit

00:04:13.450 --> 00:04:14.890
about how to use this tape deck.

00:04:14.890 --> 00:04:16.390
And one of the
first performances

00:04:16.390 --> 00:04:21.459
I can remember doing was with
a trumpet player, my brother

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:24.280
Devin who played
trumpet, a pianist.

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:27.930
I played some objects
which I had just collected,

00:04:27.930 --> 00:04:30.550
pieces of hardware,
chains, stuff like that.

00:04:30.550 --> 00:04:32.260
I had some recordings
that I played back

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:35.140
from this reel-to-reel
tape deck.

00:04:35.140 --> 00:04:39.190
And for me, this just
seemed like a normal way

00:04:39.190 --> 00:04:41.070
that someone would
want to play music.

00:04:41.070 --> 00:04:42.890
So you'd learn to
play your instrument.

00:04:42.890 --> 00:04:43.860
You'd take lessons.

00:04:43.860 --> 00:04:44.800
You'd be in ensembles.

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:48.870
You'd do all the things that
an instrumentalist would do.

00:04:48.870 --> 00:04:50.930
But at least to
me, it just seemed

00:04:50.930 --> 00:04:54.610
interesting to see
what else I could bring

00:04:54.610 --> 00:04:57.290
to the mix of playing
improvised music.

00:05:01.210 --> 00:05:03.420
And now a few decades
later, I'm really

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:04.970
still kind of doing that.

00:05:04.970 --> 00:05:11.280
So I'd like to introduce
a work that I did that in.

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:13.470
But I guess first before
I show my own work,

00:05:13.470 --> 00:05:21.210
I want to talk a
little bit about things

00:05:21.210 --> 00:05:22.721
that were in the
air when I started,

00:05:22.721 --> 00:05:24.720
a little more about things
that were in the air.

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:29.685
And two of the things that
I think had an impact on me

00:05:29.685 --> 00:05:32.530
as a young musician, and
musicians in general,

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:34.260
was number one, John Cage.

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:38.270
And mark has
mentioned that you've

00:05:38.270 --> 00:05:42.600
spoken a little bit about John
Cage's work in this class.

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:44.510
And did you talk
about Four Minutes

00:05:44.510 --> 00:05:46.920
and 33 Seconds of
Silence by chance?

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:48.710
Do you know that work?

00:05:48.710 --> 00:05:51.930
OK, so this is a work, seminal
work of 20th century music.

00:05:51.930 --> 00:05:53.550
It's a piece in three parts.

00:05:53.550 --> 00:05:57.680
And in the premier performance,
as I understand it,

00:05:57.680 --> 00:05:59.400
the pianist went to
the concert hall,

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:01.290
opened up the lid
of the piano, sat

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:04.570
for four minutes and 33 seconds,
and then closed the piano lid.

00:06:04.570 --> 00:06:06.160
And the piece was done.

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:10.820
I heard a really
interesting lecture on Cage

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:16.110
and his impact on today's
music in the last week.

00:06:16.110 --> 00:06:19.690
And the person who gave
the talk pointed out

00:06:19.690 --> 00:06:22.770
that Four Minutes and
33 Seconds of Silence

00:06:22.770 --> 00:06:27.850
was not about listening
to the sound in the room.

00:06:27.850 --> 00:06:31.500
But it was about
diverting your attention.

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:33.700
So you go to the concert
hall with the expectation

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:36.120
of seeing the lid
goes up on the piano,

00:06:36.120 --> 00:06:37.870
this virtuoso plays
this incredible piece.

00:06:37.870 --> 00:06:39.480
We're all in awe.

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:40.320
We applaud.

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:41.450
We go home.

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:44.350
And this piece was
like opening up

00:06:44.350 --> 00:06:47.905
the door to shifting your
attention away from that.

00:06:53.710 --> 00:06:56.170
And that has some really
interesting implications

00:06:56.170 --> 00:06:59.820
because I think even for
Cage-- Cage was thinking

00:06:59.820 --> 00:07:02.930
about the impact of
convention, but also

00:07:02.930 --> 00:07:04.720
the impact of big
business on music.

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:09.905
So he wrote a lecture that
was called Lecture on Nothing.

00:07:09.905 --> 00:07:13.690
And in this lecture, he talks
about the impact of media

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:17.310
culture, Time Magazine,
Life Magazine, Pepsi-Cola,

00:07:17.310 --> 00:07:20.640
and how they have a bearing
on what we understand culture

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:21.630
to be.

00:07:21.630 --> 00:07:25.780
I got a text for my son
during the last Superbowl.

00:07:25.780 --> 00:07:26.910
And Rihanna was on.

00:07:26.910 --> 00:07:30.430
And so I went to go catch
a little bit of this thing

00:07:30.430 --> 00:07:32.212
he was all excited about.

00:07:32.212 --> 00:07:33.920
And it was sponsored
by Pepsi, wasn't it?

00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:37.990
Wasn't Rihanna's Superbowl
performance sponsored by Pepsi?

00:07:37.990 --> 00:07:40.066
So, again, it was
like big business

00:07:40.066 --> 00:07:46.045
is investing a lot of time,
money, and energy on what they

00:07:46.045 --> 00:07:47.420
want us to see,
which is probably

00:07:47.420 --> 00:07:49.470
going to lead us to
buy Pepsi-Cola, which

00:07:49.470 --> 00:07:51.110
is why they're putting
money into this.

00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:55.360
But all this is to say
that one of the things that

00:07:55.360 --> 00:07:58.725
was interesting about Cage
was his music was encouraging,

00:07:58.725 --> 00:08:02.370
or his work was encouraging
us, to look outside

00:08:02.370 --> 00:08:04.590
of the prevailing
orthodox models of making

00:08:04.590 --> 00:08:09.220
music, and thinking of other
ways to think about music,

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:11.340
to approach music, to
approach working with sound.

00:08:11.340 --> 00:08:13.860
So somehow that stuck.

00:08:13.860 --> 00:08:16.550
Another thing that was
in the air at the time

00:08:16.550 --> 00:08:19.530
that I was starting to
play music was, I think,

00:08:19.530 --> 00:08:24.740
one of the first albums--
I remember at one point,

00:08:24.740 --> 00:08:26.670
for my birthday
and for Christmas,

00:08:26.670 --> 00:08:27.881
all I wanted was recordings.

00:08:27.881 --> 00:08:29.380
My mother's in the
back of the room.

00:08:29.380 --> 00:08:33.760
So I remember giving her my
wish list, like, I want records.

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:35.309
And I remember one
of the recordings

00:08:35.309 --> 00:08:39.386
I got for Christmas was
The Beatles White Album.

00:08:39.386 --> 00:08:41.010
And The Beatles White
Album had a piece

00:08:41.010 --> 00:08:42.669
called Revolution Number Nine.

00:08:42.669 --> 00:08:44.250
Do anybody know that piece?

00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:46.220
Raise your hand if
you know that piece.

00:08:46.220 --> 00:08:48.520
And goes up, OK, good.

00:08:48.520 --> 00:08:51.640
Two, OK, two people
know that piece.

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:54.910
John Lennon's wife,
Yoko Ono, no was

00:08:54.910 --> 00:08:57.890
part of a group
called Fluxus artists.

00:08:57.890 --> 00:09:03.780
And they were kind of
radical, experimental artists

00:09:03.780 --> 00:09:06.200
who did all kinds of
really fascinating things

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:10.500
with performance, with music,
with film, kind of opening up

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:16.440
all genres and medium as
tools for them to explore.

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:23.020
And through Yoko Ono, John
Lennon knew John Cage.

00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:26.982
And one of the things
he did upon becoming

00:09:26.982 --> 00:09:28.940
in contact with John Cage
and these ideas is he

00:09:28.940 --> 00:09:29.606
made this piece.

00:09:29.606 --> 00:09:32.020
And I'd like to play just
a little bit of it that's

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:34.060
called Revolution Number Nine.

00:09:34.060 --> 00:09:38.310
Now, I have colleagues who
say that this is a song

00:09:38.310 --> 00:09:42.180
because John Lennon
only made songs.

00:09:42.180 --> 00:09:44.420
So you could think
of this as a song.

00:09:44.420 --> 00:09:47.610
I always sort of thought of as a
tape piece, or a sound collage,

00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:50.330
because that's the kind of
terms I understand it in.

00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:52.098
So let me see if I
can get this to play.

00:09:57.078 --> 00:10:02.058
Can we turn this up?

00:10:02.058 --> 00:10:03.552
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:10:28.950 --> 00:10:30.710
NEIL LEONARD: I'm
going to stop it here.

00:10:33.580 --> 00:10:35.860
The piece is eight
minutes and 22 seconds.

00:10:35.860 --> 00:10:40.490
So it's a sizable piece from
this recording The White Album.

00:10:40.490 --> 00:10:43.630
So somehow this
stuff was in the air.

00:10:43.630 --> 00:10:45.840
And I think it really
had an impact on me.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:50.990
As I was alluding to
earlier, did something

00:10:50.990 --> 00:10:51.990
to my peripheral vision.

00:10:51.990 --> 00:10:54.365
It made me think that there's
something interesting there

00:10:54.365 --> 00:10:56.686
on the side to think
about and investigate.

00:10:56.686 --> 00:10:59.060
With The Beatles it wasn't
just I Want To Hold Your Hand,

00:10:59.060 --> 00:11:01.700
and these wonderful pop tunes
that I made, all of which

00:11:01.700 --> 00:11:03.510
I really enjoyed.

00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:07.060
But there was sort of
another world, other ways,

00:11:07.060 --> 00:11:09.310
to think about
working with sound.

00:11:09.310 --> 00:11:12.500
So what I would like to do
now is kind of fast forward

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:14.850
and show you fragments
of a piece I made,

00:11:14.850 --> 00:11:18.090
a long piece I made,
in the past few years.

00:11:18.090 --> 00:11:20.240
But before I do
that, I just want

00:11:20.240 --> 00:11:23.610
to invite you, if you have
questions or comments, please

00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:26.830
just blurt out your
questions or raise your hand.

00:11:26.830 --> 00:11:30.860
And I'm happy to stop
anywhere along the way

00:11:30.860 --> 00:11:33.410
and hear what's on your mind.

00:11:33.410 --> 00:11:35.180
OK?

00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:37.085
And actually, I
have a new tactic

00:11:37.085 --> 00:11:39.210
which I'm using with my
students at Berkeley, which

00:11:39.210 --> 00:11:43.370
is I don't let anybody leave the
room until they ask a question.

00:11:43.370 --> 00:11:45.150
So that works pretty well.

00:11:45.150 --> 00:11:46.570
Yes, you're leaving the room?

00:11:46.570 --> 00:11:47.861
AUDIENCE: How did he make that?

00:11:47.861 --> 00:11:49.270
Did he splice tapes together?

00:11:49.270 --> 00:11:50.970
NEIL LEONARD: Splicing
tape together,

00:11:50.970 --> 00:11:52.470
sometimes the
tapes are reversed.

00:11:52.470 --> 00:11:54.460
It sounds like
snippets of a band

00:11:54.460 --> 00:11:56.160
playing that were reversed.

00:11:56.160 --> 00:12:01.530
They had a brilliant
producer who's

00:12:01.530 --> 00:12:04.710
often referred to as the fifth
Beatle, George Martin, who

00:12:04.710 --> 00:12:06.420
had a background in
orchestral writing.

00:12:06.420 --> 00:12:09.760
So he had a very
robust skill set.

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:13.980
And if they came in
with an idea that

00:12:13.980 --> 00:12:19.540
was kind of outside the norm
of making just pop hits,

00:12:19.540 --> 00:12:22.490
or the way popular
music had been made,

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:27.050
he was often their collaborator
in going on a tangent

00:12:27.050 --> 00:12:28.270
and doing things.

00:12:28.270 --> 00:12:30.980
One example would be for
the piece Penny Lane.

00:12:30.980 --> 00:12:32.480
I don't know if you
know that piece.

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:35.320
It's a fabulous song of theirs.

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:37.850
I think it was Paul McCartney
had seen the London Symphony

00:12:37.850 --> 00:12:38.350
Orchestra.

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:41.610
He heard a Piccolo trumpet
in a Baroque concerto.

00:12:41.610 --> 00:12:43.880
He went back and told
George Martin, like,

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:44.905
that was really cool.

00:12:44.905 --> 00:12:46.280
And George Martin
said, oh, let's

00:12:46.280 --> 00:12:49.820
get the Piccolo
player from the LSO.

00:12:49.820 --> 00:12:51.290
And we'll use him on a piece.

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:54.890
So George Martin probably wrote
the part of the Piccolo trumpet

00:12:54.890 --> 00:12:56.850
on Penny Lane.

00:12:56.850 --> 00:13:00.790
And it doesn't sound like any
other track they ever made.

00:13:00.790 --> 00:13:05.503
It's a wonderful,
idiosyncratic, playful track.

00:13:08.371 --> 00:13:09.870
So, yeah, you get
to leave the room.

00:13:09.870 --> 00:13:13.130
You asked a question.

00:13:13.130 --> 00:13:16.090
I should give you a ticket.

00:13:16.090 --> 00:13:17.320
So I'm going to fast forward.

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:25.654
And I spent a few years actually
working at Mass College of Art.

00:13:25.654 --> 00:13:27.570
I thought it was going
to be a short-term job.

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:34.640
And it turned out to be an
eight year residency there and.

00:13:34.640 --> 00:13:37.370
And I kind of went in
knowing a little bit

00:13:37.370 --> 00:13:40.114
about computers, and
some teaching experience,

00:13:40.114 --> 00:13:42.030
and a little bit of
administrative experience.

00:13:42.030 --> 00:13:44.620
And they said, great,
you'll do all of that.

00:13:44.620 --> 00:13:48.660
And I ended up staying
there because they

00:13:48.660 --> 00:13:50.820
had a few really
interesting people who

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:53.160
came to work with us.

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:56.170
One was this jazz trombonist
named George Lois, who

00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:59.200
is a seminal person working
with jazz and electronics, which

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:03.280
only fueled all this
curiosity even more.

00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:07.000
John Cage was in town for a
year we did the Norton Lectures.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:10.590
And he came to Mass
Art a few times

00:14:10.590 --> 00:14:12.640
to meet with us, to
see what we were doing.

00:14:12.640 --> 00:14:14.947
I got a chance to
show him my work.

00:14:14.947 --> 00:14:17.280
There was a famous video
artist named Tony [? Allison ?]

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:18.238
who was on the faculty.

00:14:18.238 --> 00:14:20.329
So all this is to say,
I ended up staying.

00:14:20.329 --> 00:14:22.120
I really didn't think
I'd be staying there.

00:14:22.120 --> 00:14:22.620
But I did.

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:27.680
I stayed there for
eight years, kind of

00:14:27.680 --> 00:14:31.200
got involved once again in
working with visual artists.

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:33.119
Not so much me
making visual art,

00:14:33.119 --> 00:14:34.660
but collaborating
with visual artists

00:14:34.660 --> 00:14:37.650
on all kinds of projects,
performances, films, videos,

00:14:37.650 --> 00:14:41.780
dance projects, theater
projects, happenings,

00:14:41.780 --> 00:14:43.010
computer graphics with sound.

00:14:45.690 --> 00:14:52.640
And then, eventually, I married
a woman who is a visual artist.

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:56.290
And we've done a lot of
work around the world.

00:14:56.290 --> 00:14:58.060
We're doing a piece
in the upcoming Venice

00:14:58.060 --> 00:15:00.180
Biennial in May.

00:15:00.180 --> 00:15:04.890
We did piece in the
Havana Biennial last May.

00:15:04.890 --> 00:15:09.780
And so I've kind of
worked quite a bit

00:15:09.780 --> 00:15:13.490
with people who aren't
just playing saxophone,

00:15:13.490 --> 00:15:16.120
or just play with saxophonists.

00:15:16.120 --> 00:15:18.440
I've been very interested
in finding artists outside

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:20.430
of music to collaborate with.

00:15:20.430 --> 00:15:25.160
So in this kind of journey of
working with artists outside

00:15:25.160 --> 00:15:33.880
of music, I was at an Italian
estate on top of a mountain,

00:15:33.880 --> 00:15:40.550
fantastic villa that
had two incredible view.

00:15:40.550 --> 00:15:44.420
One is the marble
quarries of Carrara.

00:15:44.420 --> 00:15:49.300
So across the valley, you can
see these mountains of Carrara.

00:15:49.300 --> 00:15:52.720
And even though it's
summer and it's warm,

00:15:52.720 --> 00:15:55.260
there's just white spilling
out of the mountains, which

00:15:55.260 --> 00:16:01.810
is the fragments of marble
that didn't get schlepped away,

00:16:01.810 --> 00:16:04.060
but are just kind of like
tumbling down the mountains.

00:16:04.060 --> 00:16:09.450
So the mountains had these
sort of white residual marble,

00:16:09.450 --> 00:16:10.870
chunks of marble.

00:16:10.870 --> 00:16:13.150
The other side is
the Ligurian Sea.

00:16:13.150 --> 00:16:15.630
And so my wife and
I were asked to make

00:16:15.630 --> 00:16:18.650
a permanent installation
at this Italian estate.

00:16:18.650 --> 00:16:21.740
And the owners,
every two years they

00:16:21.740 --> 00:16:25.800
would go to the Venice
Biennial and pick an artist

00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:29.130
to commission to make a
permanent, site-specific work

00:16:29.130 --> 00:16:30.660
for their estate.

00:16:30.660 --> 00:16:32.140
And we met them,
they'd say, hey,

00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:33.470
would you do something
for our estate?

00:16:33.470 --> 00:16:35.060
And we said, yep, we
got this great idea.

00:16:35.060 --> 00:16:37.393
And they said, no, we don't
want to see your great idea.

00:16:37.393 --> 00:16:39.990
We want you to come to the
estate, look at the place,

00:16:39.990 --> 00:16:43.160
look at the territory,
and think of an idea that

00:16:43.160 --> 00:16:44.260
would work for the space.

00:16:44.260 --> 00:16:46.790
So its site specific, which
is a very important concept

00:16:46.790 --> 00:16:49.350
in visual art.

00:16:49.350 --> 00:16:53.710
So we developed a relationship
with this commissioner

00:16:53.710 --> 00:16:59.220
of private sculptures for
this private sculpture park.

00:16:59.220 --> 00:17:02.230
And one year I was going
back to visit them,

00:17:02.230 --> 00:17:05.060
and they said, you know, we
have this sculpture which you've

00:17:05.060 --> 00:17:09.450
seen that is this huge--
maybe you could draw it--

00:17:09.450 --> 00:17:14.390
it's this huge pit that's
maybe eight feet across.

00:17:14.390 --> 00:17:16.810
It's like a pit that goes
straight down the Earth.

00:17:16.810 --> 00:17:19.430
And there's just a
spiral of church bells,

00:17:19.430 --> 00:17:20.660
with no clappers in them.

00:17:20.660 --> 00:17:23.130
Very large church bells, I
mean, they might be like,

00:17:23.130 --> 00:17:26.519
from top to bottom, if
the hinge was up here,

00:17:26.519 --> 00:17:27.810
the clapper would be down here.

00:17:27.810 --> 00:17:29.790
They're very, very big.

00:17:29.790 --> 00:17:32.510
But they're turned
upside down and they're

00:17:32.510 --> 00:17:35.940
arranged in a spiral kind
of like facing the sky.

00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:38.920
And so the owner said,
would you record these bells

00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:40.810
and make something with this?

00:17:40.810 --> 00:17:43.790
And I thought, well, I have no
idea what I'll make of this,

00:17:43.790 --> 00:17:45.620
but why not?

00:17:45.620 --> 00:17:47.380
I'll record these bells.

00:17:47.380 --> 00:17:49.500
So I recorded the
sounds of these bells.

00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:50.751
And I kind of had them around.

00:17:50.751 --> 00:17:52.708
I started to play with
them, didn't really know

00:17:52.708 --> 00:17:53.800
what I'd do with them.

00:17:53.800 --> 00:18:00.910
And I met a choreographer,
also Italy, in Naples,

00:18:00.910 --> 00:18:06.400
and then she asked me for a
composition for a dance piece.

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:10.630
And I thought, OK, well
I have these sounds

00:18:10.630 --> 00:18:12.620
I made with these bells.

00:18:12.620 --> 00:18:17.390
So maybe it would be
interesting to do something

00:18:17.390 --> 00:18:18.170
with these belts.

00:18:18.170 --> 00:18:22.440
So I'm going to play just a
fragment of this recording

00:18:22.440 --> 00:18:23.845
that I made.

00:18:36.260 --> 00:18:38.290
So you know when you
take a JPEG image

00:18:38.290 --> 00:18:43.110
and you stretch it
horizontally, all of a sudden

00:18:43.110 --> 00:18:45.050
the image is unrecognizable?

00:18:45.050 --> 00:18:47.150
This is sort of what
I've done with sound.

00:18:47.150 --> 00:18:49.130
And some of this I did
with some free software

00:18:49.130 --> 00:18:49.960
which I could show you.

00:18:49.960 --> 00:18:50.960
There's commercial software.

00:18:50.960 --> 00:18:52.020
There's free software.

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:54.394
Lots of different software
does time stretching of audio.

00:18:54.394 --> 00:18:56.230
So this could be
two seconds of audio

00:18:56.230 --> 00:18:58.500
that's stretched
out for a minute.

00:19:06.570 --> 00:19:09.210
The computer's going
to kind of sputter.

00:19:09.210 --> 00:19:12.597
And then this is sounds of just
bells straight because I wanted

00:19:12.597 --> 00:19:14.180
the listeners in the
dance performance

00:19:14.180 --> 00:19:20.068
to be able to hear an actual
bell so this wash of sound

00:19:20.068 --> 00:19:22.068
in the background would
make some kind of sense,

00:19:22.068 --> 00:19:24.528
would have some context.

00:19:24.528 --> 00:19:25.512
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:19:42.240 --> 00:19:44.255
NEIL LEONARD: Now,
the dance performance

00:19:44.255 --> 00:19:46.435
was 40 minutes long.

00:19:46.435 --> 00:19:49.261
So it's a very
kind of slow, kind

00:19:49.261 --> 00:19:50.817
of glacially moving performance.

00:19:54.090 --> 00:19:55.930
So nothing in the music
happens too quickly.

00:19:55.930 --> 00:19:58.955
The music goes through a
lot of different phases.

00:19:58.955 --> 00:20:02.102
But each phase is
maybe five minutes.

00:20:02.102 --> 00:20:03.590
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:20:39.655 --> 00:20:40.946
NEIL LEONARD: And this goes on.

00:20:40.946 --> 00:20:42.904
But essentially, these
were recordings of bells

00:20:42.904 --> 00:20:45.860
that I put in a program called
Spear, which we could look at.

00:20:45.860 --> 00:20:51.410
And I began playing with ways
to time stretch the audio,

00:20:51.410 --> 00:20:53.860
listening to what
sounded interesting,

00:20:53.860 --> 00:20:55.350
throwing away a lot of stuff.

00:20:55.350 --> 00:21:01.040
I kind of went into a phase
where when I make a piece,

00:21:01.040 --> 00:21:03.770
I want to have a
phase in the beginning

00:21:03.770 --> 00:21:07.910
where I call it sort of like
your work-- a research phase,

00:21:07.910 --> 00:21:11.480
research, slash,
play, slash, failure.

00:21:11.480 --> 00:21:14.935
Meaning, I take sounds,
I put them in a software.

00:21:14.935 --> 00:21:15.935
I play around with them.

00:21:15.935 --> 00:21:21.160
I research what I can do,
knowing that I probably

00:21:21.160 --> 00:21:23.580
have time to throw
a lot of these away.

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:26.192
So I'm not doing this the
day before the performance.

00:21:26.192 --> 00:21:27.900
This might be a few
weeks or a few months

00:21:27.900 --> 00:21:29.260
before the performance.

00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:32.709
And I want to build
in time to experiment,

00:21:32.709 --> 00:21:34.750
knowing that a lot of the
experiments won't work.

00:21:34.750 --> 00:21:37.160
So out of many of
those experiments,

00:21:37.160 --> 00:21:38.850
I came out with this file.

00:21:38.850 --> 00:21:39.830
Sent it to the dancer.

00:21:39.830 --> 00:21:42.620
The dancer said, that's really
going to work for the idea

00:21:42.620 --> 00:21:44.110
that she was thinking of.

00:21:44.110 --> 00:21:50.330
And then she proposed a site
to do this performance, which

00:21:50.330 --> 00:21:52.970
was Mount Vesuvius.

00:21:52.970 --> 00:21:59.010
So Mount Vesuvius, as you
know, is the volcanic mountain

00:21:59.010 --> 00:22:01.660
that erupted and buried Pompeii.

00:22:01.660 --> 00:22:03.900
It is still an active volcano.

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:10.000
There are people who occupy the
side of the volcano pretty much

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:15.492
against, or in defiance of,
kind of zoning limitations

00:22:15.492 --> 00:22:17.200
because the authorities
don't want people

00:22:17.200 --> 00:22:19.190
to live in this volcano
because it's dangerous.

00:22:19.190 --> 00:22:23.680
The people live there all
have gas masks in their house,

00:22:23.680 --> 00:22:26.030
because the biggest
the problem is

00:22:26.030 --> 00:22:28.600
the toxic gas that
comes from the volcano.

00:22:28.600 --> 00:22:30.234
So in any case, there
was an art center

00:22:30.234 --> 00:22:31.650
on the side of
this mountain where

00:22:31.650 --> 00:22:33.830
we staged this performance.

00:22:33.830 --> 00:22:40.250
And it kind of grounded
the whole piece right then,

00:22:40.250 --> 00:22:43.262
because I begin to think of
what is it I'm working on?

00:22:43.262 --> 00:22:44.470
I'm working with these bells.

00:22:44.470 --> 00:22:46.136
We're doing something
on Mount Vesuvius.

00:22:46.136 --> 00:22:47.850
How am I going to
begin to kind of focus

00:22:47.850 --> 00:22:49.420
on an idea for this piece?

00:22:53.566 --> 00:22:56.807
And there's an author
named Murray Schafer who

00:22:56.807 --> 00:22:58.890
wrote a book called The
Tuning of the World, which

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:01.490
has been republished under
the title Soundscape.

00:23:01.490 --> 00:23:02.630
You can find it on Amazon.

00:23:02.630 --> 00:23:05.360
It's probably in the library
here, Murray H. Schafer.

00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:07.080
And one of the things
he writes about

00:23:07.080 --> 00:23:12.940
is that for any environment
there's a keynote sound.

00:23:12.940 --> 00:23:15.560
There is a sound
that we human beings

00:23:15.560 --> 00:23:18.090
associate with
every environment.

00:23:18.090 --> 00:23:21.290
So with this
environment right now,

00:23:21.290 --> 00:23:27.440
it's probably the sound of the
fan on the video projector,

00:23:27.440 --> 00:23:29.410
or maybe the hiss coming
out of the speakers.

00:23:29.410 --> 00:23:31.010
This would be
keynote sound here.

00:23:31.010 --> 00:23:33.100
Perhaps in the
hallway, it's the sound

00:23:33.100 --> 00:23:39.770
of footsteps within this space
that you know is very long.

00:23:39.770 --> 00:23:41.260
It's not very wide.

00:23:41.260 --> 00:23:43.705
And it's a fairly
reverberant space.

00:23:43.705 --> 00:23:46.915
So every place you
go, there are sounds

00:23:46.915 --> 00:23:50.371
that let you know
you're in that place.

00:23:50.371 --> 00:23:52.370
When I was standing at
the subway the other day,

00:23:52.370 --> 00:23:56.310
the metro in Brookline,
I was recording the sound

00:23:56.310 --> 00:23:58.870
of the train because I've
taken that train, the D Line,

00:23:58.870 --> 00:23:59.890
for ages.

00:23:59.890 --> 00:24:02.640
And if I heard that
sound in my sleep,

00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:05.750
I would know, Green Line,
lightrail vehicle, Green Line.

00:24:09.772 --> 00:24:11.480
So I would say that
one of the things I'm

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:14.180
really interested
in doing is thinking

00:24:14.180 --> 00:24:17.980
of pieces that have
a particular meaning,

00:24:17.980 --> 00:24:20.385
have a meaning that's
tied to a particular site.

00:24:22.990 --> 00:24:24.100
That fascinates me.

00:24:24.100 --> 00:24:27.342
And that's a way to kind of get
out of doing what I always do.

00:24:27.342 --> 00:24:29.050
So if I'm going to
work at Mount Vesuvius

00:24:29.050 --> 00:24:30.800
I don't want to do just
what I do in Boston.

00:24:30.800 --> 00:24:32.299
I want to do something
which is kind

00:24:32.299 --> 00:24:34.336
of specific to a
performance which

00:24:34.336 --> 00:24:35.960
is going to premiere
at Mount Vesuvius.

00:24:35.960 --> 00:24:42.210
If I do something in
a rice paddy in Japan,

00:24:42.210 --> 00:24:44.470
what's something about
a rice paddy in Japan

00:24:44.470 --> 00:24:46.660
that I wouldn't
think of in Boston?

00:24:46.660 --> 00:24:52.400
How can I respond to the
site where the work is?

00:24:52.400 --> 00:24:55.750
So one of the ways
to respond to a site

00:24:55.750 --> 00:24:58.230
where you're working
as a musician is

00:24:58.230 --> 00:25:08.977
to think of the keynote
sounds, and play with those.

00:25:08.977 --> 00:25:11.310
What are the sounds that are
typical to that environment

00:25:11.310 --> 00:25:13.850
that kind of tell you
you're in that environment

00:25:13.850 --> 00:25:17.370
that you can play with?

00:25:17.370 --> 00:25:20.790
I should say, very briefly,
that one of the things which

00:25:20.790 --> 00:25:24.180
is fascinating in Murray
Schafer's book and his ideas,

00:25:24.180 --> 00:25:33.090
is that he also kind of points
to this way of reflecting

00:25:33.090 --> 00:25:39.920
on your environment is an
integral part of literature

00:25:39.920 --> 00:25:42.770
that we know, that we've
known for centuries.

00:25:42.770 --> 00:25:50.910
So, for example, for Dickens
to talk about England

00:25:50.910 --> 00:25:56.920
in the period of Oliver
Twist, cobblestone streets

00:25:56.920 --> 00:25:59.220
have a particular sound,
horses on cobblestone streets

00:25:59.220 --> 00:26:00.700
have a particular sound.

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:02.810
Those sounds are
sounds that Dickens

00:26:02.810 --> 00:26:05.330
is very aware of being very
important to your understanding

00:26:05.330 --> 00:26:06.460
of that place.

00:26:06.460 --> 00:26:09.480
Those are parts
of Dickens' world.

00:26:09.480 --> 00:26:13.990
Tolstoy, same, the example
I like most is Dante.

00:26:13.990 --> 00:26:17.325
In Dante's Inferno, when Virgil
and Dante head off to hell,

00:26:17.325 --> 00:26:19.200
they decide they're
going to go over to hell,

00:26:19.200 --> 00:26:20.116
see what's over there.

00:26:20.116 --> 00:26:21.000
They pass Cerberus.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:22.540
They make it to
the mouth of hell.

00:26:22.540 --> 00:26:24.540
There are no stars above hell.

00:26:24.540 --> 00:26:26.680
The damned don't
get to have stars.

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:29.080
There's a black sky above hell.

00:26:29.080 --> 00:26:31.290
And because the sky is
black and there's no light,

00:26:31.290 --> 00:26:33.505
there are two paragraphs
of The Inferno

00:26:33.505 --> 00:26:37.320
that the contact with
hell is an audio contact.

00:26:37.320 --> 00:26:38.960
It's an audible contact.

00:26:38.960 --> 00:26:41.190
They hear the sounds
of the damned.

00:26:41.190 --> 00:26:44.450
And there is a two paragraph
description of the sighs,

00:26:44.450 --> 00:26:46.400
and the gasping,
and the kind of toil

00:26:46.400 --> 00:26:50.090
that these people are
experiencing in hell.

00:26:50.090 --> 00:26:51.970
So all this is fascinating
to me because it

00:26:51.970 --> 00:26:57.210
means that Dante, Tolstoy,
Dickens, were audio artists.

00:26:57.210 --> 00:27:02.600
They were interested in oral
analysis, or oral reflection,

00:27:02.600 --> 00:27:04.580
of their environment.

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:08.530
So this is part of
something we can do.

00:27:08.530 --> 00:27:10.970
Our environment might be
like the vending machines

00:27:10.970 --> 00:27:12.319
downstairs.

00:27:12.319 --> 00:27:14.610
They may be the sound of
going up and down the hallway,

00:27:14.610 --> 00:27:16.340
or going up and down
the staircases which

00:27:16.340 --> 00:27:17.990
have wonderful echoes.

00:27:17.990 --> 00:27:19.950
It could be the sound
of radiators just

00:27:19.950 --> 00:27:21.940
kind of flapping.

00:27:21.940 --> 00:27:25.710
But these are
sounds which can be

00:27:25.710 --> 00:27:27.740
really interesting to work with.

00:27:27.740 --> 00:27:30.500
So when I began to work
on this piece, which

00:27:30.500 --> 00:27:33.750
I'm going to play not
the rest of, but more of,

00:27:33.750 --> 00:27:36.570
I just wanted to say that
it occurred to me that there

00:27:36.570 --> 00:27:40.220
was this wonderful opportunity
in that one of the most

00:27:40.220 --> 00:27:46.900
incredible sounds ever in Italy
was Mount Vesuvius blowing up.

00:27:46.900 --> 00:27:51.230
And period accounts
of that explosion

00:27:51.230 --> 00:27:55.722
say that the explosion could
be heard 100 kilometers away.

00:27:55.722 --> 00:27:57.180
So you could
practically be in Rome

00:27:57.180 --> 00:28:01.300
and hear the sound of
this colossal boom.

00:28:01.300 --> 00:28:07.550
The colossal mountain now
is kind of like a big mouth

00:28:07.550 --> 00:28:11.570
waiting to erupt again,
like these bells.

00:28:11.570 --> 00:28:13.620
The mouths the bells were
all facing the ceiling.

00:28:13.620 --> 00:28:18.170
So this became kind
of an idea that I

00:28:18.170 --> 00:28:23.080
began to play with and work
with in the piece, this idea

00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:25.600
of a kind of silent tongue.

00:28:30.920 --> 00:28:36.200
As the piece evolved--
and I'll play you

00:28:36.200 --> 00:28:39.360
maybe five minutes of a kind of
finished version of the piece,

00:28:39.360 --> 00:28:41.750
