and your assignment, which
is the next we'll talk about,

00:46:59.310 --> 00:47:08.460
is that this semester I hosted
a composer named Hans Tutschku.

00:47:08.460 --> 00:47:11.250
Hans Tutschku is the director
of the computer music

00:47:11.250 --> 00:47:13.300
program at Harvard.

00:47:13.300 --> 00:47:16.400
And if you ever get
a chance, there's

00:47:16.400 --> 00:47:22.430
probably a concert coming up
probably at the end of April.

00:47:22.430 --> 00:47:26.950
And he does concerts with what
he calls the hydra system.

00:47:26.950 --> 00:47:31.400
The hydra system is a
collection of 40 speakers.

00:47:31.400 --> 00:47:34.100
And you sit inside
the 40 speakers.

00:47:34.100 --> 00:47:37.850
And it's a little bit like going
to a cathedral, where there's

00:47:37.850 --> 00:47:42.340
like a dome, and the dome
has a painting on it.

00:47:42.340 --> 00:47:44.530
If you ever go to the
Vatican, for example, there's

00:47:44.530 --> 00:47:46.130
this beautiful dome,
with this ring,

00:47:46.130 --> 00:47:49.290
with this text which
is really important.

00:47:49.290 --> 00:47:51.330
And it's just a
great experience.

00:47:51.330 --> 00:47:52.209
It's an installation.

00:47:52.209 --> 00:47:53.000
It's a work of art.

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:54.460
The dome is a work of art.

00:47:54.460 --> 00:47:56.320
This is the sonic dome.

00:47:56.320 --> 00:48:00.250
And there are three
rings of speaker.

00:48:00.250 --> 00:48:02.210
One's at ear level.

00:48:02.210 --> 00:48:05.180
One kind of maybe six
feet above ear level,

00:48:05.180 --> 00:48:06.580
and like 12 feet
above ear level.

00:48:06.580 --> 00:48:10.180
And the rings the rings
go really wide, smaller,

00:48:10.180 --> 00:48:12.880
and smallest.

00:48:12.880 --> 00:48:14.700
So he came to Berkeley.

00:48:14.700 --> 00:48:16.222
And the students
were all excited.

00:48:16.222 --> 00:48:17.430
Here's this guy from Harvard.

00:48:17.430 --> 00:48:18.650
He's got to be important.

00:48:18.650 --> 00:48:19.736
And he uses 40 speakers.

00:48:19.736 --> 00:48:21.610
So he's got to be more
sophisticated than us.

00:48:21.610 --> 00:48:23.300
He knows things we don't know.

00:48:23.300 --> 00:48:27.690
And the fascinating thing was he
showed us these pieces he made,

00:48:27.690 --> 00:48:30.150
which were fantastic
piece of music.

00:48:30.150 --> 00:48:31.610
He made them like--
I'm recording

00:48:31.610 --> 00:48:34.485
this lecture on this little
Sony handheld recorder.

00:48:34.485 --> 00:48:36.700
it's not that expensive.

00:48:36.700 --> 00:48:39.300
He made all his recordings
with a little Zoom

00:48:39.300 --> 00:48:42.120
handheld recorder, like $400.

00:48:42.120 --> 00:48:45.720
And he was saying one of things
he likes to do is wave it.

00:48:45.720 --> 00:48:49.170
So if he's playing
an antique piano,

00:48:49.170 --> 00:48:50.280
which is all out of tune.

00:48:50.280 --> 00:48:51.900
And he's recording the sound.

00:48:51.900 --> 00:48:56.530
He'll move, he'll sweep,
like a visual artist

00:48:56.530 --> 00:48:57.610
would move a camera.

00:48:57.610 --> 00:49:02.010
If a visual artist is going
to shoot a video of a rock,

00:49:02.010 --> 00:49:04.400
they're probably not going
to put the video on a tripod

00:49:04.400 --> 00:49:05.250
to shoot the rock.

00:49:05.250 --> 00:49:06.750
I mean, there's a
pretty good chance

00:49:06.750 --> 00:49:10.210
they'll want to move to show us
different aspects of this rock.

00:49:10.210 --> 00:49:12.620
Well, this is what Hans
loves to do with microphones,

00:49:12.620 --> 00:49:14.630
move them across the surface.

00:49:14.630 --> 00:49:16.880
Because his argument
is if you have a gone,

00:49:16.880 --> 00:49:19.720
and you hit the gong, and
you move it by your ear,

00:49:19.720 --> 00:49:22.130
the gong sounds one way
if it's 30 feet away,

00:49:22.130 --> 00:49:24.775
one way if it's 10 feet away,
and one way it it's very soft

00:49:24.775 --> 00:49:26.120
and you're right next to it.

00:49:26.120 --> 00:49:28.530
Those are three completely
different sounds.

00:49:28.530 --> 00:49:29.880
They're all gong.

00:49:29.880 --> 00:49:34.390
But the details you get
are radically different.

00:49:34.390 --> 00:49:38.160
So one thing I want
to point out is

00:49:38.160 --> 00:49:40.850
that the selection
of the materials

00:49:40.850 --> 00:49:42.820
is a major part of the work.

00:49:42.820 --> 00:49:49.160
And one of the things Hans said,
which I also had been doing,

00:49:49.160 --> 00:49:52.410
but I'd never really thought
about in quite the way he

00:49:52.410 --> 00:49:56.540
was discussing it, was he only
uses sounds he records himself.

00:49:56.540 --> 00:49:58.910
And he's been doing this
for a long time, decades.

00:49:58.910 --> 00:50:00.630
And so he has all
kinds of sounds

00:50:00.630 --> 00:50:02.620
he's made all over the world.

00:50:02.620 --> 00:50:05.740
But the important thing
about all the sounds

00:50:05.740 --> 00:50:08.770
is that he has a
memory of recording

00:50:08.770 --> 00:50:12.140
each one, of choosing
to record each one.

00:50:12.140 --> 00:50:16.540
So of these thousands
of sounds he might have,

00:50:16.540 --> 00:50:20.290
he has a visceral
experience that's

00:50:20.290 --> 00:50:22.560
associated with every sound.

00:50:22.560 --> 00:50:27.580
So those bells I recorded,
are bells I recorded.

00:50:27.580 --> 00:50:29.680
And I know the
weight of the bell.

00:50:29.680 --> 00:50:30.895
I know the color of the bell.

00:50:30.895 --> 00:50:32.270
I know where it
was in the Earth.

00:50:32.270 --> 00:50:33.860
I remember what it was like
to put the mic on there.

00:50:33.860 --> 00:50:35.450
I remember how hot
it was that day.

00:50:35.450 --> 00:50:37.535
I remember how we kind
of hit them with hammers,

00:50:37.535 --> 00:50:39.922
did all kinds of things to
try to get a sound out of them

00:50:39.922 --> 00:50:41.880
because they weren't free
standing bells really

00:50:41.880 --> 00:50:44.300
made to be struck.

00:50:44.300 --> 00:50:48.560
Same with the vocalist, I
remember hearing this vocalist,

00:50:48.560 --> 00:50:50.820
and we had a discussion
about getting something

00:50:50.820 --> 00:50:52.830
that would work in this piece.

00:50:52.830 --> 00:50:56.325
So all those memories are
valuable when you go back

00:50:56.325 --> 00:50:57.950
to your material
because otherwise it's

00:50:57.950 --> 00:50:59.900
just a sound file.

00:50:59.900 --> 00:51:02.400
Like every other sound file,
maybe I like it, maybe I don't.

00:51:02.400 --> 00:51:09.740
But because you have been
involved in physically

00:51:09.740 --> 00:51:12.520
recording and
capturing that sound,

00:51:12.520 --> 00:51:14.490
it's as if it was in your hands.

00:51:14.490 --> 00:51:16.970
You have a kind of
tactile relation

00:51:16.970 --> 00:51:18.900
to the sound that you
wouldn't have otherwise.

00:51:18.900 --> 00:51:21.990
Now here's what I'm going
to ask you guys to do.

00:51:30.230 --> 00:51:33.600
So I understand you've
worked not only with Mark,

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:35.800
but you've work with
my colleague Tom Hall.

00:51:35.800 --> 00:51:39.330
And I'm actually playing a
concert with Tom Hall on Sunday

00:51:39.330 --> 00:51:42.150
at a place called The
Outpost with a bassist named

00:51:42.150 --> 00:51:45.044
Jamaaladeen Tacuma, who
is known for his work

00:51:45.044 --> 00:51:46.710
with Ornette Coleman,
very good bassist.

00:51:51.040 --> 00:51:53.660
Mark has also told
me that you work

00:51:53.660 --> 00:51:56.610
in pairs, or sometimes
groups of three.

00:51:56.610 --> 00:52:00.545
And with your pair,
I'm going to ask

00:52:00.545 --> 00:52:03.830
you to make a
collaborative improvisation

00:52:03.830 --> 00:52:05.710
with audio recordings.

00:52:05.710 --> 00:52:09.720
And your goal is to, with
your partner or partners,

00:52:09.720 --> 00:52:13.595
create small sound
library to utilize

00:52:13.595 --> 00:52:15.220
in a two to three
minute improvisation.

00:52:18.965 --> 00:52:21.340
And you're going to prepare
a performance that integrates

00:52:21.340 --> 00:52:22.930
the playback of
some of the sounds

00:52:22.930 --> 00:52:25.360
you record in this performance.

00:52:30.260 --> 00:52:34.060
So let me ask you one thing.

00:52:34.060 --> 00:52:35.680
How do you like to improvise?

00:52:35.680 --> 00:52:37.770
And how do you
improvise in this class?

00:52:37.770 --> 00:52:41.200
Is it more along the lines
of free improvisation?

00:52:41.200 --> 00:52:45.840
Are people improvising with
a chord, or with a tonic,

00:52:45.840 --> 00:52:47.460
or is it all of the above?

00:52:47.460 --> 00:52:50.470
PROFESSOR: We've done
modal improvisation.

00:52:50.470 --> 00:52:54.080
We've done graphic notation,
like Cage's notations.

00:52:54.080 --> 00:52:58.390
We've created our own scripts
for that, and then done that.

00:52:58.390 --> 00:53:01.570
We've done a lot of free.

00:53:01.570 --> 00:53:05.940
We've done a lot of with
small little parameters.

00:53:05.940 --> 00:53:08.370
Indian concepts
of Phil Scarf too.

00:53:08.370 --> 00:53:11.460
NEIL LEONARD: So all
of those are fine.

00:53:11.460 --> 00:53:15.840
Any of the approaches
to improvisation

00:53:15.840 --> 00:53:17.720
that you have been
working with this semester

00:53:17.720 --> 00:53:20.080
that you want to use for the
improvisation you do for me

00:53:20.080 --> 00:53:24.964
next week, or I'll do with
you next week, is welcome.

00:53:24.964 --> 00:53:27.130
It's going to be much more
interesting for all of us

00:53:27.130 --> 00:53:29.312
if you're doing something
which you like to do so.

00:53:29.312 --> 00:53:30.770
And I don't know
you that well so I

00:53:30.770 --> 00:53:34.900
don't want to tell you what
to do with the improvisation

00:53:34.900 --> 00:53:40.010
except I want you to use
whatever technology you have

00:53:40.010 --> 00:53:43.560
at your disposal, which might
be your iPhone-- probably

00:53:43.560 --> 00:53:45.760
everybody has a phone
that can record audio.

00:53:45.760 --> 00:53:46.770
It could be a phone.

00:53:46.770 --> 00:53:48.230
It could be an iPad.

00:53:48.230 --> 00:53:52.620
It could be a portable
recording device.

00:53:52.620 --> 00:53:56.220
And I want you to make
a collection of sounds.

00:53:56.220 --> 00:53:58.170
Say how many, it could be four.

00:53:58.170 --> 00:54:00.800
It could be 10.

00:54:00.800 --> 00:54:04.630
And I want you to use
this original material

00:54:04.630 --> 00:54:07.750
as source material for
this improvisation.

00:54:07.750 --> 00:54:14.500
So it can be valuable
to go to the internet,

00:54:14.500 --> 00:54:19.744
and find an audio archive, and
get audio, and do a piece based

00:54:19.744 --> 00:54:21.160
on what you found
on the Internet.

00:54:21.160 --> 00:54:22.980
And I can think of some
really cool examples.

00:54:22.980 --> 00:54:24.896
But I'm going to encourage
you not to do that.

00:54:24.896 --> 00:54:31.480
So I actually want you
to think about the sounds

00:54:31.480 --> 00:54:37.780
that-- you don't have to leave
where you live, where you work,

00:54:37.780 --> 00:54:39.490
where you study.

00:54:39.490 --> 00:54:44.490
Within this part of the
world that you travel in,

00:54:44.490 --> 00:54:47.850
you can get the sounds there.

00:54:47.850 --> 00:54:51.080
So plan a recording in a
location that you frequent

00:54:51.080 --> 00:54:53.362
daily, your walk to school,
your apartment, your job.

00:54:53.362 --> 00:54:55.070
The idea is to listen
to your environment

00:54:55.070 --> 00:54:57.867
and discover new details that
help divert the audience's

00:54:57.867 --> 00:54:59.700
attention from the
typical mode of listening

00:54:59.700 --> 00:55:00.640
to everyday sounds.

00:55:00.640 --> 00:55:05.720
So when you think of
the role of audio,

00:55:05.720 --> 00:55:12.905
of using audio recordings,
in improvisation,

00:55:12.905 --> 00:55:13.780
you get a few things.

00:55:13.780 --> 00:55:15.790
One is you get what
Luciano Berio said

00:55:15.790 --> 00:55:19.650
is we open the sound
pallet up to everything.

00:55:19.650 --> 00:55:24.670
Now, you could prepare
your guitar, for example.

00:55:24.670 --> 00:55:27.400
If you play acoustic guitar, or
cello, or piano, or whatever,

00:55:27.400 --> 00:55:28.685
you could prepare your guitar.

00:55:28.685 --> 00:55:32.020
Do you know that is to prepare
your guitar in the John Cage

00:55:32.020 --> 00:55:33.120
sense?

00:55:33.120 --> 00:55:35.070
In the John Cage,
preparing a piano

00:55:35.070 --> 00:55:37.660
meant like putting
bolts in the strengths.

00:55:37.660 --> 00:55:41.120
I'm not going to encourage you
to do that with this piano.

00:55:41.120 --> 00:55:46.560
But people put paper clips,
erasers, and screws and stuff

00:55:46.560 --> 00:55:47.150
in the piano.

00:55:47.150 --> 00:55:48.524
And it changed
the way it sounds.

00:55:48.524 --> 00:55:51.710
There's a beautiful Cage
recording of prepared piano.

00:55:51.710 --> 00:55:54.110
It makes it sound kind
of like a gamelan.

00:55:54.110 --> 00:55:56.840
You could prepare
your instrument.

00:55:56.840 --> 00:55:59.220
As long as you're
making the recording,

00:55:59.220 --> 00:56:01.540
I'm probably not going to
say, you can't do that.

00:56:01.540 --> 00:56:04.470
You could record
sounds of cars whizzing

00:56:04.470 --> 00:56:08.040
by you on Memorial Drive.

00:56:08.040 --> 00:56:10.920
But one of the things
which I didn't really

00:56:10.920 --> 00:56:14.030
put in writing here, but
I think is important,

00:56:14.030 --> 00:56:20.930
is if you can find either
one keynote sound, or one

00:56:20.930 --> 00:56:25.430
idea about sound, that you'd
like to play with, it might

00:56:25.430 --> 00:56:36.780
be-- you might get
more out of that then

00:56:36.780 --> 00:56:38.872
recording like 15
completely different sounds.

00:56:38.872 --> 00:56:41.080
If you want to record 15
completely different sounds,

00:56:41.080 --> 00:56:43.955
I'm not going to stop you, but
I'm actually encourage you to--

00:56:43.955 --> 00:56:44.830
Think of it this way.

00:56:47.820 --> 00:56:50.680
If you had a play, if we were
doing theater for next week,

00:56:50.680 --> 00:56:53.440
and we said, let's make a play.

00:56:53.440 --> 00:56:58.050
And there are going
to be five actors.

00:56:58.050 --> 00:57:01.450
The first actor is probably
not going to come on the scene

00:57:01.450 --> 00:57:03.261
and then never come back again.

00:57:03.261 --> 00:57:05.260
They're probably not going
to just say one thing

00:57:05.260 --> 00:57:05.884
and then leave.

00:57:05.884 --> 00:57:11.090
Although, now that I say this,
I can think of some examples

00:57:11.090 --> 00:57:11.900
where that happens.

00:57:11.900 --> 00:57:15.100
In fact, I went to go see
Mahler's Third at the BSO.

00:57:15.100 --> 00:57:18.640
And there's a singer who
sang literally five lines.

00:57:18.640 --> 00:57:20.580
And she came out halfway.

00:57:20.580 --> 00:57:23.600
This is 100 minute symphony.

00:57:23.600 --> 00:57:27.931
She came out halfway through,
sang literally five lines,

00:57:27.931 --> 00:57:29.930
and stood on the stage
for the rest of the time.

00:57:29.930 --> 00:57:31.850
It was really weird.

00:57:31.850 --> 00:57:33.100
It was a great piece of music.

00:57:33.100 --> 00:57:34.750
But it was weird.

00:57:34.750 --> 00:57:40.205
But the point is this, if
you're thinking prepared guitar,

00:57:40.205 --> 00:57:46.370
or if you're thinking of the
sound of opening and closing

00:57:46.370 --> 00:57:48.400
windows in your
apartment, or whatever

00:57:48.400 --> 00:57:51.660
it is that you're
interested in, what does it

00:57:51.660 --> 00:57:55.870
sound like in the quad, or
between the buildings here?

00:57:58.590 --> 00:58:03.740
You get sort of a theme and
variation potential, or a kind

00:58:03.740 --> 00:58:10.440
of multiple perspective feature
in your piece, if you will,

00:58:10.440 --> 00:58:16.320
if you have more than one
recording of a certain thing.

00:58:16.320 --> 00:58:17.425
So let me ask you.

00:58:17.425 --> 00:58:19.300
I'm just going to pick
your brains right now.

00:58:19.300 --> 00:58:23.840
If you were to choose
something to record

00:58:23.840 --> 00:58:26.790
to include in an
improvisation-- I

00:58:26.790 --> 00:58:28.636
don't want your
final answer now.

00:58:28.636 --> 00:58:30.510
But I'm just going to
pick on all of you guys

00:58:30.510 --> 00:58:32.420
just to kind of get
the conversation going.

00:58:32.420 --> 00:58:32.970
What's your name?

00:58:32.970 --> 00:58:33.620
AUDIENCE: James.

00:58:33.620 --> 00:58:35.078
PROFESSOR: James,
so what would you

00:58:35.078 --> 00:58:36.652
do if you had to pick right now?

00:58:36.652 --> 00:58:39.564
AUDIENCE: I think
the sounds of riding

00:58:39.564 --> 00:58:43.090
the bus would be interesting,
the doors opening and closing,

00:58:43.090 --> 00:58:46.022
or stop requests.

00:58:46.022 --> 00:58:48.740
I feel like you could play a lot
with all the different sounds

00:58:48.740 --> 00:58:49.320
involved.

00:58:49.320 --> 00:58:51.130
PROFESSOR: For sure,
and it would also

00:58:51.130 --> 00:58:55.700
have the built in connotation
of the piece's emotion.

00:58:55.700 --> 00:58:56.784
The piece is stopping.

00:58:56.784 --> 00:58:57.700
The piece is starting.

00:58:57.700 --> 00:58:59.562
The motion of the
piece is stopping.

00:58:59.562 --> 00:59:00.520
The motion is starting.

00:59:00.520 --> 00:59:03.490
I had a teacher who when I went
back to my master's degree,

00:59:03.490 --> 00:59:09.290
a really wonderful composer
named Bob Brookmeyer.

00:59:09.290 --> 00:59:11.240
And he said music is motion.

00:59:11.240 --> 00:59:13.880
Anything you do to impede the
motion has to be questioned.

00:59:13.880 --> 00:59:16.740
It doesn't mean to you
can't impede the motion.

00:59:16.740 --> 00:59:21.890
But think twice if you're
going to impede the motion.

00:59:21.890 --> 00:59:24.050
Well, this is a
piece about a bus.

00:59:24.050 --> 00:59:26.240
Or a piece that's including
sounds from the bus,

00:59:26.240 --> 00:59:29.140
so that's kind of
like a built in idea.

00:59:29.140 --> 00:59:32.530
The bus has stops.

00:59:35.380 --> 00:59:35.950
Good.

00:59:35.950 --> 00:59:37.820
Perfect.

00:59:37.820 --> 00:59:38.930
Your name again?

00:59:38.930 --> 00:59:42.185
AUDIENCE: Vineet.

00:59:42.185 --> 00:59:43.268
The sounds of an elevator.

00:59:43.268 --> 00:59:48.020
NEIL LEONARD:
Elevator, sure, good.

