01:09:40.710 --> 01:09:41.833
If that makes sense.

01:09:41.833 --> 01:09:44.720
NEIL LEONARD: Good, good.

01:09:44.720 --> 01:09:48.770
I do want to say one thing
about noise and banging doors.

01:09:48.770 --> 01:09:54.920
I just want to say
a couple that does

01:09:54.920 --> 01:10:03.870
sound art, Janet Cardiff and
George Miller is her partner.

01:10:14.090 --> 01:10:16.490
And Janet Cardiff just did
a piece in a New York armory

01:10:16.490 --> 01:10:17.850
in the last 12 months.

01:10:20.700 --> 01:10:23.820
But she's famous for
making these pieces where

01:10:23.820 --> 01:10:27.600
they were like audio walks,
where you would headphones on.

01:10:27.600 --> 01:10:29.920
And it would be like she
was on the walk with you.

01:10:29.920 --> 01:10:31.378
And she would tell
you where to go.

01:10:31.378 --> 01:10:32.940
There was a Central Park one.

01:10:32.940 --> 01:10:36.200
And as you're walking with
this person who's not there,

01:10:36.200 --> 01:10:42.620
it's like a disembodied voice,
she begins to tell you a story.

01:10:42.620 --> 01:10:45.040
And you're getting kind of
wrapped up in the story.

01:10:45.040 --> 01:10:47.560
And the next thing, a
helicopter flies right by you.

01:10:47.560 --> 01:10:49.226
And you turn around,
and it's not there.

01:10:49.226 --> 01:11:01.390
So it's a kind of a
talk kind of reshapes

01:11:01.390 --> 01:11:04.990
your audio experience
on a specific

01:11:04.990 --> 01:11:06.720
walk that she's designed it for.

01:11:06.720 --> 01:11:09.840
So, again, a site-specific
piece of art.

01:11:09.840 --> 01:11:13.590
But she and George
Miller were invited

01:11:13.590 --> 01:11:19.710
to do a piece at the
Eastern State Penitentiary

01:11:19.710 --> 01:11:21.740
in Pennsylvania, which
is in Philadelphia.

01:11:21.740 --> 01:11:25.120
It's a penitentiary
which is infamous

01:11:25.120 --> 01:11:28.340
for, among other
things, it was maybe

01:11:28.340 --> 01:11:30.274
the first penitentiary
in the United States

01:11:30.274 --> 01:11:31.690
where they had
this big experiment

01:11:31.690 --> 01:11:33.140
in solitary confinement.

01:11:33.140 --> 01:11:37.810
So one of the wings, or
maybe in all of the wings,

01:11:37.810 --> 01:11:41.280
prisoners were isolated
in cells by themselves

01:11:41.280 --> 01:11:43.970
with only a Bible with the idea
that if they were by themselves

01:11:43.970 --> 01:11:46.300
with a Bible they
would have nothing

01:11:46.300 --> 01:11:47.950
to do but reform themselves.

01:11:47.950 --> 01:11:51.580
And I think that it did not
become the model for reform.

01:11:56.720 --> 01:11:59.880
But they now commission
artworks in the Eastern State

01:11:59.880 --> 01:12:00.770
Penitentiary.

01:12:00.770 --> 01:12:08.950
And so what they did is they
made these kind of robots--

01:12:08.950 --> 01:12:12.670
I won't call them robots--
but these beaters that

01:12:12.670 --> 01:12:14.600
were motorized.

01:12:14.600 --> 01:12:18.120
And they were maybe
in this one corridor

01:12:18.120 --> 01:12:22.470
there were like 162
cell blocks, both sides

01:12:22.470 --> 01:12:25.010
of the corridor, first
and second floor.

01:12:25.010 --> 01:12:28.844
And they had at least
one of these beaters

01:12:28.844 --> 01:12:30.260
in every one of
these cell blocks.

01:12:30.260 --> 01:12:32.850
Now, this corridor had
not been renovated.

01:12:32.850 --> 01:12:35.240
It was still like totally
dilapidated, paint

01:12:35.240 --> 01:12:37.300
chipping all over the
place, water damage.

01:12:37.300 --> 01:12:38.560
But they never cleaned it out.

01:12:38.560 --> 01:12:39.976
So there was still
some furniture,

01:12:39.976 --> 01:12:42.420
which means like beds,
bed pans, whatever it as.

01:12:42.420 --> 01:12:44.609
So they put beaters
in every cell block.

01:12:44.609 --> 01:12:45.650
And they controlled them.

01:12:45.650 --> 01:12:47.680
They were controlled
by computer.

01:12:47.680 --> 01:12:50.370
And they did exactly
what I was saying,

01:12:50.370 --> 01:12:53.260
which is where I
got the idea, is

01:12:53.260 --> 01:12:55.430
they made this 16 minute score.

01:12:55.430 --> 01:12:57.110
And they did it with a computer.

01:12:57.110 --> 01:12:58.480
And they did it in a sequence.

01:12:58.480 --> 01:13:00.000
They did it actually
in the same one

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:02.450
I'm using now, Logic, and
the piano roll notation.

01:13:02.450 --> 01:13:04.820
And everyone little
note in the piano roll

01:13:04.820 --> 01:13:08.440
was a different hammer
in a different cell.

01:13:08.440 --> 01:13:11.190
So in some parts
of the recording.

01:13:11.190 --> 01:13:13.840
It's very pointalistic.

01:13:13.840 --> 01:13:17.374
You would hear a sound
from one cell, then

01:13:17.374 --> 01:13:19.290
something from the other
side of the corridor.

01:13:19.290 --> 01:13:21.370
There's kind of a
race section where

01:13:21.370 --> 01:13:23.680
they're all pounding
out a rhythm.

01:13:23.680 --> 01:13:27.614
But they're kind
of different sounds

01:13:27.614 --> 01:13:30.030
that-- I mean, you can only
imagine what the inmates would

01:13:30.030 --> 01:13:35.120
have thought if
whatever it would be,

01:13:35.120 --> 01:13:37.255
really 150 years later.

01:13:37.255 --> 01:13:43.910
This is long-- this is
like totally over, pretty

01:13:43.910 --> 01:13:44.580
horrible place.

01:13:48.490 --> 01:13:49.790
But it was a banging piece.

01:13:49.790 --> 01:13:50.650
Lockers bang.

01:13:50.650 --> 01:13:53.530
So it was a piece that
was all about banging,

01:13:53.530 --> 01:13:57.480
banging in a corridor, kind
of almost like a prison riot

01:13:57.480 --> 01:14:01.570
kind of vibe from the
recording I've heard of it.

01:14:01.570 --> 01:14:03.700
I didn't actually see the piece.

01:14:03.700 --> 01:14:05.090
But they had a structure too.

01:14:05.090 --> 01:14:06.930
And part of the structure
was have a rave.

01:14:06.930 --> 01:14:09.061
So there was kind
of a beat, or I

01:14:09.061 --> 01:14:11.590
don't know if you could call
it a recognizable groove.

01:14:11.590 --> 01:14:15.952
But there was sort of
like a periodic thumping

01:14:15.952 --> 01:14:17.410
